					<latex-image><xi:include href="curves.d/quantity-vs-rate-3.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

		</sidebyside>

		<sidebyside valign="top" widths="31.5% 31.5% 31.5%"> <!-- calculated widths 35.2% 35.2% 35.2%  -->

			<figure>
				<caption> Quantity and rate both decreasing. </caption>
				<image xml:id="image-curves-quantity-vs-rate-4">
					<shortdescription>Typical graph shape when quantity and rate are both decreasing.</shortdescription>
					<!-- TODO description -->
					<latex-image><xi:include href="curves.d/quantity-vs-rate-4.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

			<figure>
				<caption>
					Quantity increasing then decreasing,
					but rate always decreasing. </caption>
				<image xml:id="image-curves-quantity-vs-rate-5">
					<shortdescription>
						Typical graph shape when quantity increases then decreases,
						but rate is always decreasing.
					</shortdescription>
					<!-- TODO description -->
					<latex-image><xi:include href="curves.d/quantity-vs-rate-5.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

			<figure>
				<caption> Quantity increasing but rate decreasing. </caption>
				<image xml:id="image-curves-quantity-vs-rate-6">
					<shortdescription>Typical graph shape when quantity is increasing but rate is decreasing.</shortdescription>
					<!-- TODO description -->
					<latex-image><xi:include href="curves.d/quantity-vs-rate-6.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

		</sidebyside>

	</sbsgroup>

</figure>

<p>
Notice that these representative graphs are split into two groups based on a common feature,
depending on whether the rate is increasing or decreasing:
each graph with an increasing rate exhibits a curve that opens upward,
whereas each graph with an increasing rate exhibits a curve that opens downward.
</p>

<definition>
	<title>Concavity and inflection points</title>
	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m>q(t)</m> is a twice-differentiable function on domain <m>a \lt t \lt b</m>.
		<ul>
			<li>
				If <m>q''(t) \gt 0</m> at all points on that domain,
				then we say that <m>q</m> is <term>concave up</term> there.
			</li>
			<li>
				If <m>q''(t) \lt 0</m> at all points on that domain,
				then we say that <m>q</m> is <term>concave down</term> there.
			</li>
			<li>
				If <m>t = t^\ast</m> is in the domain of <m>q</m> and at a boundary between concave up and down domains,
				then we say that <m>q</m> has an <term>inflection point</term> there.
			</li>
		</ul>
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<remark><p>
	Since the second derivative of <m>q</m> is the <em>first</em> derivative of <m>q'</m>,
	domains of concavity for <m>q</m> coincide with domains of increase/decrease for <m>q'</m>,
	and inflection points for <m>q</m> must be critical points for <m>q'</m>.
	That means that
	<alert>
		to determine inflection points,
		we should look for points where <m>q''(t)</m> is either <m>0</m> or undefined
	</alert>.
	However,
	just as with critical points versus local extremes,
	note that having one of those two conditions does <em>not</em> necessarily mean that <m>q</m> will have an inflection point there.
</p></remark>

<warning><p>
	A common mistake for beginning students is to use critical points for <m>q</m> in their analysis of concavity and inflection points.
	While some functions will coincidentally have <m>q''(t) = 0</m> at some of the same <m>t</m>-values where <m>q'(t) = 0</m> occurs,
	in general only points with <m>q''(t) = 0</m> (or <m>q''(t)</m> undefined) should be considered as potential inflection points.
</p></warning>

<!-- <example>

	<p>
	The square function <m>f(t) = t^2</m> has both
	<md><mrow> f'(0) \amp = 0 \amp f''(0) \amp = 0 </mrow></md>.
	While it has a local minimum at the critical point <m>t = 0</m>,
	it does not have a point of inflection there,
	since the graph is a parabola that is concave up on its entire domain.
	</p>

	<p>
	On the other hand,
	the cube function <m>g(t) = t^3</m> also has both
	<md><mrow> g'(0) \amp = 0 \amp g''(0) \amp = 0 </mrow></md>.
	While it has an inflection point at <m>t = 0</m> because the graph switches from concave down to concave up there,
	it does not have a local extreme there because it increases on its entire domain.
	</p>

	TODO two graphs

</example> -->

<example xml:id="example-curves-concavity">
	<title>Determining concavity</title>

	<p>
	Let's continue <xref ref="example-curves-domains-of-inc-dec" />,
	where we've already determined the domains of increase and decrease for
	<md> q(t) = \frac{2 t^2}{t^2 - 1} </md>.
	Let's now ask Sage to calculate the second derivative for us.
	</p>

	<sage>
		<input>
			var('t')
			q(t) = 2 * t^2 / (t^2 - 1)
			qpp = q.derivative().derivative()
			print(qpp.simplify_full())
		</input>
		<output> 4*(3*t^2 + 1)/(t^6 - 3*t^4 + 3*t^2 - 1) </output>
	</sage>

	<p>
	That denominator is ugly,
	let's have Sage factor it for us.
	</p>

	<sage>
		<input>
			var('t')
			factor(t^6 - 3*t^4 + 3*t^2 - 1)
		</input>
		<output> (t + 1)^3*(t - 1)^3 </output>
	</sage>

	<p>
	So now we have <md> q''(t) = \frac{4 (3 t^2 + 1)}{ {(t + 1)}^3 {(t - 1)}^3 } </md>.
	Note that the numerator is always positive,
	so <m>q''(t) = 0</m> is not possible.
	This function is undefined at <m>t = \pm 1</m>,
	but so is the original function <m>q(t)</m>,
	so those cannot be inflection points.
	However, they could still be boundaries between different concavities for <m>q</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	Since the numerator is always positive,
	to solve the inequalities
	<md><mrow> q''(t) \amp \gt 0 \amp q''(t) \amp \lt 0 </mrow></md>
	we only need to look at the denominator.
	We see:
	<ul>
		<li>
			<m>{(t + 1)}^3</m> is negative on <m>t \lt -1</m>
			and positive on <m>t \gt -1</m>
		</li>
		<li>
			<m>{(t - 1)}^3</m> is negative on <m>t \lt 1</m>
			and positive on <m>t \gt 1</m>.
		</li>
	</ul>
	Putting these together, we have that <m>q</m> is
	<ul>
		<li> concave up on <m>t \lt -1 </m> and on <m>t \gt 1</m> </li>
		<li> concave up down on <m>-1 \lt t \lt 1 </m>. </li>
	</ul>
	</p>

</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-curves-shape">
<title>Graph trends</title>

<p>
Computers are great at drawing graphs for us,
but they have some draw backs.
<ul>
	<li>
		A restricted viewport means you never know if you are seeing all the important features and behaviour of the the graph,
		no matter how far you zoom out.
	</li>
	<li>
		Computer-generated graphs do not perform well with functions whose values <q>explode</q> quickly, especially near singularities.
	</li>
</ul>
Essentially,
the problem is that a computer can only show you what you ask it to show you,
and is unforgiving in its accuracy.
As humans we can sacrifice some accuracy and use what we have learned in this and previous chapters
to sketch a <em>total graphical picture</em> of the behaviour of a function's graph,
one that we can be sure captures all of the important features of the graph.
To do this,
we <em>don't</em> plot a whole bunch of points and blindly <em>connect the dots</em>.
Instead, we only plot important points
(for example, intercepts, critical points, inflection points)
and then connect these using our knowledge of the graph's behaviour between them
(increasing/decreasing, concave up/down, singularities, long-term/ancient behaviour).
</p>

<example>
	<title>Sketching a graph</title>

	<p>
	Let's finish analyzing the function
	from <xref ref="example-curves-domains-of-inc-dec" />
	and <xref ref="example-curves-concavity" />:
	<md> q(t) = \frac{2 t^2}{t^2 - 1} </md>.
	We already know:
	<ul>
		<li> increasing on <m>t \lt -1</m> and <m>-1 \lt t \lt 0</m> </li>
		<li> decreasing on <m>0 \lt t \lt 1</m> and <m>t \gt 1</m> </li>
		<li> concave up on <m>t \lt -1 </m> and on <m>t \gt 1</m> </li>
		<li> concave up down on <m>-1 \lt t \lt 1 </m>. </li>
	</ul>
	To this we can add:
	<ul>
		<li>
			intercepts both axes at the origin,
			since <m>q(0) = 0</m>,
			and there are no other axis intercepts
		</li>
		<li> singularities at <m>t = -1</m> and <m>t = 1</m> </li>
		<li><p>
			long-term behaviour
			<md> \frac{2 t^2}{t^2 - 1} \to 2 \qquad\text{as}\qquad t \to \infty </md>
		</p></li>
		<li><p>
			ancient behaviour
			<md> \frac{2 t^2}{t^2 - 1} \to 2 \qquad\text{as}\qquad t \to -\infty </md>.
		</p></li>
	</ul>
	We can also combine some of these pieces of information.
	<ul>
		<li>
			Since the graph increases up to the intercept at <m>q(0) = 0</m>
			and then decreases away,
			there must be a local maximum there.
		</li>
		<li>
			Since <m>q</m> increases on <m>t \lt -1</m>,
			the graph must be above the horizontal asymptote <m>y = 2</m> at the far left of the graph,
			and must increase away from it so that eventually <m>y \to \infty</m> as <m>t = -1^-</m> on the left of the vertical asymptote at <m>t = -1</m>.
		</li>
		<li>
			Since <m>q</m> also increases on <m>-1 \lt t \lt 0</m>,
			the graph must increase away from the vertical asymptote at <m>t = -1</m>,
			so <m>y \to -\infty</m> as <m>t \to -1^+</m>.
		</li>
		<li>
			With similar reasoning we can conclude
			<md>
				<mrow> y \to -\infty \qquad\text{as}\qquad t \to 1^- </mrow>
				<mrow> y \to  \infty \qquad\text{as}\qquad t \to 1^+ </mrow>
			</md>
			and that the graph must decrease down to the horizontal asymptote at <m>y = 2</m> from above at the far right of the graph.
		</li>
	</ul>
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-curves-sketch-1">
		<caption>Graph of <m>q(t) = 2 t^2 / (t^2 - 1)</m>.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-curves-sketch-1" width="100%">
			<shortdescription>Graph of an analyzed function.</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="curves.d/sketch-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<p>
Here is a general procedure one can follow to sketch a graph that contains all the important features of the function.
The steps do not necessarily all need to be completed,
nor do they necessarily need to be completed in the stated order.
</p>

<algorithm xml:id="procedure-curves-sketching">
	<title>Curve-sketching procedure</title>

	<p><ol>

		<li>
			Determine the domain of the function,
			and sketch in any vertical asymptotes.
		</li>

		<li>
			Determine the long-term and ancient behaviour,
			and sketch in any horizontal or slant asymptotes.
		</li>

		<li> Determine and plot any axis intercepts. </li>

		<li>
			Determine any critical points,
			calculate the output values at those points,
			and plot their approximate locations.
		</li>

		<li>
			Determine the domains of increase and decrease.
			Use the <xref ref="pattern-curves-first-derivative-test" text="title" /> to classify each critical point as a local minimum, local maximum, or a saddle point.
		</li>

		<li>
			Determine the domains of concavity.
			Determine any inflection points,
			calculate the output values at those points,
			and plot their approximate locations.
		</li>

		<li>
			Finally, sketch the graph between the asymptotes and plotted points,
			being sure that the sketch reflects the increase/decrease/concavity information on each subdomain.
		</li>

	</ol></p>

</algorithm>

<p>
Here is one final example.
Verifying the provided information is left to you,
the reader.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Using the curve-sketching procedure</title>
	<p>
	For function <md> q(t) = \frac{t^3}{t^2 + 1} </md>,
	we have derivative and second derivative
	<md><mrow>
		q'(t) \amp = \frac{t^2 (t^2 + 3)}{(x^2 + 1)^3}
		\amp
		q''(t) \amp = \frac{2 t (3 - t^2)}{(t^2 + 1)^3}
	</mrow></md>.
	</p>

	<p>
	Here is the information requested by the <xref ref="procedure-curves-sketching" text="title" />.

	<ol>

		<li>
			<title>Domain</title>
			<p>
			The whole real number line.
			No singularities.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<title>Long-term/ancient behaviour</title>
			<p>
			<md>
				<mrow>
					q(t) \amp \to \infty \amp\amp\text{as}\amp t \to \infty
					\amp
					q(t) \amp \to -\infty \amp\amp\text{as}\amp t \to -\infty
				</mrow>
			</md>
			So no horizontal asymptotes,
			but we can divide
			<md> \frac{t^3}{t^2 + 1} = t - \frac{t}{t^2 + 1} </md>,
			with <md> \frac{t}{t^2 + 1} \to 0 \qquad\text{as}\qquad t \to \pm \infty </md>,
			so we have a slant asymptote of <m>y = t</m>.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<title>Intercepts</title>
			<p>
			Only at the origin,
			as <m>q(0) = 0</m>.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<title>Critical points</title>
			<p>
			Only at <m>q'(0) = 0</m>,
			and we already know that <m>q(0) = 0</m>.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<title>Increase/decrease</title>
			<p>
			Increasing on the entire domain,
			so the critical point at the origin is a saddle point.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<title>Concavity</title>
			<p><ul>
				<li> Concave up on <m>t \lt -\sqrt{3}</m> and again on <m>0 \lt t \lt \sqrt{3}</m>. </li>
				<li> Concave down on <m>-\sqrt{3} \lt t \lt 0</m> and again on <m>t \gt \sqrt{3}</m>. </li>
				<li>
					Inflection points at
					<md><mrow> q(-\sqrt{3}) \amp = - \frac{3 \sqrt{3}}{4} \amp q(0) \amp = 0 \amp q(\sqrt{3}) = \frac{3 \sqrt{3}}{4} </mrow></md>.
				</li>
			</ul>
			</p>
		</li>

	</ol>

	</p>

	<p>
	And here is the graph.
	Being a computer-generated graph,
	it's a bit difficult to see the change in concavity at inflection points <m>t = \pm \sqrt{3}</m>.
	But the graph <em>must</em> change concavity at these points,
	because it is impossible for the graph to approach the slant asymptote from below at the far right of the graph with a concave-up orientation,
	and similarly for the approach to the slant asymptote at the far left of the graph.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-curves-sketch-2">
		<caption>Graph of <m>q(t) = t^3 / (t^2 + 1)</m>.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-curves-sketch-2" width="42.6%">
			<shortdescription>Graph of an analyzed function.</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="curves.d/sketch-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

</section>


